text: No, I mean, you hit exactly on it. And this was kind of the, I don't want to say joke, but this was in 2012, 13, 14, this was kind of the thing that we kept coming up against, both internally and externally, was we don't want to put the long-term equity funds out of business because we need them. If anything, we kind of refined that narrative and that clarity that we got from 2011 and said, long-term equity funds are... Our position was that individually long-term equity funds, both individually and collectively, add value. We would argue that there's obviously more idiosyncratic risk at the individual level. Even when you collect a basket of long-term equity funds, you're dealing with these kind of uncompensated, what I'm going to call business risk factors. But it was tricky. I mean, we ended up... The fund of funds business, the guys ended up retiring, the third-party marketing firm, different pieces got sold to different groups. And so this hedge fund replication business ended up being bought by VanEck Global, the ETF shop. And that was one of the things they discussed is they're like, well, you know, are you guys worried about putting the hedge fund business out of business? And the simple answer was the incentives to be a hedge fund manager, at least back then, the incentives to be a hedge fund manager were still great enough. And everybody... There's always going to be a lot of guys that think their approach is a little different. It's worth taking a swing at. And that was kind of our position was that they're always going to be there. Collectively, the crowd sourcing, the statistical crowd sourcing approach works on this asset class. But the other part of it too is we were very clear to investors, the clone portfolio is never going to be up 30%. It's never... By definition, it's always... It's going to track or should track the indices. So if you're a smaller endowment or a smaller pension or just a smaller institutional investor, and you're only investing in one or two long-term equity funds, it probably... And you have access to them and you don't mind the business risks that you're underwriting. It probably does make sense. And I think that's a good point. It makes sense to just invest directly with managers. One could argue that you could find the guys that are going to do better than the rest of the group. We pivoted our approach to go after the really big guys. This hospital foundation was the perfect client. They were so big that they needed to benchmark part of their active portfolio in these clone portfolios. And we landed on that as the perfect case study of how these fit in the ecosystem in a way that's kind of preserves the homeostasis and isn't too disruptive.
